			</div>
</figure>
</p>

<p><span class="large">In</span> the hallway at work, Susan told me that she and her husband had gotten to talk about everything before the end, and for that she was grateful. I told her I felt gratitude, too: for a good death, for forty years, for my children and grandchildren. In the sixteen months since Fernando&rsquo;s death, I had been cultivating gratitude. But, standing there, I wondered if he and I had talked about <em>everything</em>. There was so much that had passed unspoken between us. Sometimes I&rsquo;d thought I just knew what he wanted, but what if I&rsquo;d been wrong? This worried me, now that I couldn&rsquo;t ask him. What if I hadn&rsquo;t understood him, or he hadn&rsquo;t understood me?</p>

<p>I said to Susan, &ldquo;I feel like we are not yet untangled.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><span class="large">When</span> Kathryn and I went to San Xavier Mission to light a candle in Fernando&rsquo;s memory, I started to pray for his spirit to be free, and I imagined a hawk soaring. But then, in my prayer, I said, <em>No. I am not ready for his spirit to be released. I still need him near me.</em></p>

<p>That&rsquo;s when I understood that I hadn&rsquo;t known what I was saying on the night before he died, when I&rsquo;d told him, &ldquo;I love you, Fernando, but I let you go.&rdquo; I still don&rsquo;t know what that meant. You can let the body go, because you have no choice, but the body isn&rsquo;t everything.</p>

<p>Maybe that&rsquo;s why we say, &ldquo;I <em>lost</em> my husband.&rdquo; My dreams, right after Fernando died, were always of losing him: I was on a train trying to get to him, but I didn&rsquo;t know where he was, and my cellphone wouldn&rsquo;t work. I wasn&rsquo;t sad, only bewildered. I was sure I would eventually find him. Then one morning I dreamed we were making love, and he got up before I came, and I said, <em>Come back here. I&rsquo;m not finished</em>. But he wanted to put the <em>menudo</em> on the stove and start the coffee. <em>Come back here</em>, I said again, suddenly angry. I heard him rattling the pots in the kitchen.<em> I am so mad at you</em>, I yelled, <em>I could stab you in the heart!</em></p>

<p>In one dream he was sitting across the room from me, at the foot of the bed. <em>Beth</em>, he said, <em>I had been very sick for eight years</em>.</p>

<p>When I woke up, I knew it was true. The last time he&rsquo;d undergone a treatment for hepatitis <span class="smallcaps">C</span>, in 2004, the doctors had taken him off the drug, because it wasn&rsquo;t working. He had seemed tired after that round of treatments. He had never fully recovered. And then I remembered: when my mother had died in 2006, I&rsquo;d said, &ldquo;No one else gets to die for at least six years.&rdquo; Why had I said that?</p>

<p>Recently I dreamed Fernando was sick, and for some reason I was moving him from hotel to hotel, as if I didn&rsquo;t want him to be found. When I finally got him into a room and lay down on the bed next to him, he seemed frail. We were stretched out, facing each other. I could feel his breath on my face. We kissed, our lips touching quickly, as if there wasn&rsquo;t much time. And then I handcuffed my wrist to his so they couldn&rsquo;t take him.</p>

<p>After we went to San Xavier, I confessed to Kathryn that I hadn&rsquo;t been able to pray for Fernando&rsquo;s spirit to be free. &ldquo;I&rsquo;m too selfish,&rdquo; I said. She said she hadn&rsquo;t prayed to God at all; she&rsquo;d prayed to her dad. &ldquo;Was that wrong?&rdquo; she asked. I said that if she believed God is in all of us, then, when she prayed to her dad, she was praying to God.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><span class="large">One</span> night, shortly after Fernando died, Kathryn and I were sleeping together. Just as I was falling asleep, she asked if I had touched her forehead. She&rsquo;d felt someone touch her there, the way her dad would have done if he were tucking her in. I told her it wasn&rsquo;t me. It must have been him. And I rolled over and felt sorry for myself that he hadn&rsquo;t visited me. I closed my eyes, and in a vision &mdash; not a dream &mdash; I saw my mother standing in a dark place, holding a lantern in one hand and opening a door with the other. Through the door I could see light, and I understood that he had gone there, to the light place. My mother was letting me know.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><span class="large">On</span> Monday Fernando stayed in bed all day. He didn&rsquo;t go to the living room. So if I remember something that happened in the living room, then I know it was either Saturday or Sunday. If the memory takes place in the bedroom, then I know it was Monday. That morning the hospice nurse came, and I signed the <span class="smallcaps">DNR</span>, and she explained the use of the morphine and the sedative and what to look for to tell whether death was near. Then Kathryn, Michael, and I all went back to the bedroom with the nurse, and she asked if we had any scissors. I got a pair, and we cut Fernando out of his pajamas and put a hospital gown on him. &ldquo;I&rsquo;m cold,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;I can&rsquo;t feel my legs.&rdquo; I asked if he was afraid, and he said no.</p>

<p>Outside the bedroom, the hospice nurse told Michael it could still be days &mdash; weeks, even. I started to panic then. What if Kathryn and I couldn&rsquo;t take care of him by ourselves? Wasn&rsquo;t there a bed for him in the hospice? No, the hospice was evidently a service, not a place to which he could be taken. And if we took him to the hospital, doctors would prolong the dying process. Michael and my brother-in-law Bernie had been helping us move Fernando, but they couldn&rsquo;t stay. &ldquo;We can&rsquo;t move him by ourselves,&rdquo; I told the nurse. And she said sometimes an eighty-five-year-old woman has to take care of her dying husband by herself. &ldquo;How does she do that?&rdquo; I asked. The hospice nurse said she didn&rsquo;t know.</p>

<p>At one point that afternoon I decided to lie down next to Fernando. I realized it might be the last time I would lie in bed with him. It was possible he wouldn&rsquo;t make it through the night. I was lying on my side, my hand on his arm. Tears were sliding over the bridge of my nose and into my ear, which reminded me of being a little girl. The sun was streaming in through the window, and I was listening to him breathe. I could hear other people in the house, family members, and I thought, I&rsquo;m just going to lie here and pretend I&rsquo;m asleep. I&rsquo;m not going to share him with anyone today. They can come in and say what they want, but I&rsquo;m going to stay here.</p>

<p>I wanted to scoot even closer to him and throw my leg over his legs and my arm over his chest and put my head on his shoulder, which was how I always fell asleep. But I was lying on the wrong side of him, and he was so swollen with fluids I was afraid I would hurt him.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><span class="large">Yesterday</span> morning I looked up from an article at the breakfast table and wished I could read it to Fernando. What I miss most is his physical presence: touching him, feeling him touch me, kissing, sex &mdash; we always had great sex. But I also miss our conversations, our walks, those long Sunday-morning discussions we used to have about fate or politics or something we&rsquo;d read. He was a much faster reader than I was. He&rsquo;d say, &ldquo;Hurry up and read that. I want to talk with you about it.&rdquo; Such a pain in the butt. Is there something wrong with me that I don&rsquo;t seem as bereft as some widows, that I&rsquo;m handling it so well? That&rsquo;s what everyone says: &ldquo;You are handling it so well.&rdquo; I know he is dead. I just can&rsquo;t believe we will be separated forever. Whoever wrote, &ldquo;Till death do us part,&rdquo; didn&rsquo;t know what he was talking about.</p>

<p>I read a few years ago that a mother carries her children&rsquo;s genes. We all know the child carries the mother&rsquo;s genes, but when mothers are tested, their blood also contains their children&rsquo;s genes. And the second child carries some of the first child&rsquo;s genes, and so on. All of this genetic material is circulated through the amniotic fluid in the mother. And so Fernando&rsquo;s genes are inside of me, because I carried both his children. (Actually three, since there was one miscarriage.) When I say, &ldquo;I feel as if he is still alive inside me,&rdquo; maybe it&rsquo;s because he is still with me, not only in memory or in spirit, but literally in my blood and in my cells.</p>

<p>Poet Angie Estes writes, &ldquo;In paradise, / Dante says, we will have only a memory / of having had a memory.&rdquo; As the spirits&rsquo; memories of this world dissipate, as their ties to us lessen, as their visitations become fewer and farther between, is this when our grief starts to wane? What will still bind us if the grief goes? Are we afraid to stop grieving, because it means we&rsquo;ve stopped loving?</p>

<p>Another poet, Aleda Shirley, writes, &ldquo;my dead / have their own dead to find &amp; so must disperse.&rdquo;</p>

<p>As I write this, Fernando&rsquo;s father is dying in an <span class="smallcaps">ICU</span>.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><span class="large">When</span> Fernando&rsquo;s mother died, she waited until everyone had left the house except for his father, and then she said, &ldquo;Something passed through me,&rdquo; and she closed her eyes and took a few breaths and died. I believed Fernando was capable of orchestrating his exit this way. He would go when he was ready.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><span class="large">Fernando</span> died on Monday night. Before he did, he turned in bed and with great effort said, &ldquo;Beth. I have a place.&rdquo; And that&rsquo;s when I asked him to wait for me. I said it might be years, but it wouldn&rsquo;t seem so long to him. I told him I was happy he had a place and wouldn&rsquo;t go to the gray place. Both our children were in the room, so he could see all of us. Sometimes I feel guilty that I didn&rsquo;t give them each time to be alone with him, but it felt right for the four of us to be together. I sang him some of the songs I used to sing to the kids when I was putting them to bed. I remember Kathryn putting her hand on my back, and Michael behind her, as if they were giving me their strength so that I could sing without my voice breaking.</p>

<p>I remember putting Fernando&rsquo;s hand over my heart, and my hand over his. I remember him raising his arms so he could breathe. I remember his eyes. He had been asleep all day, but now he was fully awake, and in his gaze I saw all his love, all his faith, everything he wanted to say but couldn&rsquo;t. I felt a part of me rush out to him, as if to comfort him, or to go with him. He looked away. I could see that it was hard for him. When he&rsquo;d told me I had to let him go, I hadn&rsquo;t realized that he&rsquo;d been trying to let us go, too.</p>
														</div>


				
